{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0542c5a1-cfbc-446d-87cc-fdffbe9225ce","content":"There's nothing in this repository about that topic. Here's the general guidance:\n\n## Recovering a crash dump on macOS without `createdump`\n\nNativeAOT apps don't ship `createdump` (it's a CoreCLR tool), so you rely on **macOS system-level crash reporting**:\n\n1. **Enable core dumps** in your shell:\n   ```bash\n   ulimit -c unlimited\n   ```\n\n2. **Check for Apple crash logs** after the crash:\n   ```\n   ~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   /Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n   ```\n   These `.ips` / `.crash` files contain stack traces and register state.\n\n3. **Locate the core file** (if generated):\n   ```\n   /cores/core.<pid>\n   ```\n   macOS writes core dumps here when `ulimit -c` is set. You may also need:\n   ```bash\n   sudo sysctl kern.coredump=1\n   ```\n\n4. **Analyze with `lldb`**:\n   ```bash\n   lldb --core /cores/core.<pid> /path/to/your/app\n   ```\n   Then use `bt` (backtrace), `frame select`, `register read`, etc.\n\n5. **If `/cores/` is empty**, check that SIP isn't blocking core dumps and that the disk has space. On newer macOS versions, core dumps for hardened-runtime binaries may be suppressed — re-sign without the hardened runtime for debugging:\n   ```bash\n   codesign --remove-signature ./your-app\n   ```\n\nThe Apple `.crash`/`.ips` logs (step 2) are usually the quickest path to a stack trace.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"696a09d2-81c3-4f61-905e-c59054e153ad","outputTokens":411,"requestId":"9813:6A01C:7959C14:860D783:69F40750"},"id":"050866f3-fe24-4ac6-956f-d2c199244d46","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:52:26.820Z","parentId":"a9d3ae1b-d56d-40d7-aaa2-2d2e0b92ef29"}
